abstract.p:
This paper introduces a class of insulin-glucose-glucocorticoid impulsive systems in the treatment of patients with diabetes to consider the effect of glucocorticoids. The existence and uniqueness of the positive periodic solution of the impulsive model at double fixed time is confirmed for type 1 diabetes mellitus (T1DM) using the \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Lambert\;W$$\end{document} function. Further, the global asymptotic stability of the positive periodic solution is achieved following Floquet multiplier theory and comparison principle. Additionally, the permanence of the system is confirmed in type 2 diabetes mellitus (T2DM) via the comparison theorem. Numerical analysis verifies the results of theoretical calculations and indicates that combining therapeutic strategies under hormonal interactions with the dose of exogenous insulin and glucocorticoid medicines within organisms provides more reasonable clinical strategies.

sec.p:
The body’s hormonal balance is complex interplay of numerous hormones interacting and influencing one another; glucocorticoids, in particular, perform a crucial role in modulating the function of insulin. Glucocorticoids are active substances secreted by the zona fasciculata of the adrenal cortex that regulate carbohydrate, lipid, and protein metabolism. While physiological levels of glucocorticoids are crucial for maintaining normal bodily functions, elevated levels can lead to dysregulation of glucose and lipid metabolism, ultimately causing conditions such as Cushing’s syndrome or metabolic syndrome, which are characterized by central obesity and insulin resistance. Key organs and tissues affected by insulin resistance include liver, adipose tissue, bone, and skeletal muscle. Research has demonstrated that prolonged exposure to high glucocorticoid levels can result in liver disease and metabolic disorders in visceral, adipose, and skeletal muscle tissues, exacerbating insulin resistance6. The mechanisms through which glucocorticoids induce insulin resistance can be categorized as follows7,8: 
Glucocorticoids and hepatic insulin resistance;
Glucocorticoids and adipose tissue insulin resistance;
Glucocorticoids and skeletal muscle tissue insulin resistance;
Effects of glucocorticoids on pancreatic \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\beta$$\end{document} cells;
Central nervous system glucocorticoid signaling and insulin resistance.In the central nervous system, elevated physiological concentrations of glucocorticoids affect energy metabolism primarily by modulating the hypothalamic sympathetic and parasympathetic systems, which can lead to metabolic abnormalities such as Cushing’s syndrome. Currently, oral glucocorticoids are widely utilized in the treatment of both acute and chronic adrenal insufficiency, as well as allergic diseases. However, improper dosing of glucocorticoids can significantly impact insulin action, potentially inducing diabetes or complicating diabetes management. Thus, investigating the interaction mechanisms between glucocorticoids and insulin is both urgent and important.

In this paper, to more accurately capture the pharmacokinetics of glucocorticoids in the context of diabetes treatment, we introduce a three-compartment model to describe the coupling dynamics of glucocorticoids. The model incorporates the following variables: insulin I(t), glucose G(t), and glucocorticoid H(t). Among them, insulin is secreted by islet \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
