In this paper, considering the antagonistic effect of glucocorticoids on insulin, we proposed a class of pulse model system under exogenous insulin injection and oral glucocorticoid-like medicine treatment strategy. By using the properties of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Lambert \; W$$\end{document} function and Floquet multiplier theory, we obtained the global asymptotically stable positive periodic solution of system (1) when \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sigma _1=0$$\end{document} (T1DM). And then proved the permanence of T2DM by the comparison theorem. The numerical simulation clearly demonstrated that the co-administration of insulin and glucocorticoid-like drugs in diabetic patients elicits distinct glucose concentrations, as compared to the use of exogenous insulin drugs alone. It necessitates a comprehensive understanding of hormone interactions in vivo.
